LABEL: vaccine protection assay
definition: An assay that is used to detect if a vaccine protects a host against infection of virulent pathogen after vaccine immunization.

LABEL: CFU measurement assay
definition: CFU measurement assay is an assay that measures the colony forming unit (CFU) of a bacterium in a specific location (e.g., spleen of a mouse).

LABEL: CFU reduction assay
definition: CFU reduction assay is an assay that measures the reduction of the colony forming units of infected pathogens in vaccine-vaccinated animals compared to nonvaccinated animals.

LABEL: host survival to pathogen challenge after vaccination
immune response detection assay
definition: An assay that is used to detect the immune response of a host to vaccination of a vaccine.

LABEL: vaccine persistence assay
definition: An assay that measures the persistent survival of live vaccine in a host in vivo.

LABEL: vaccine protection efficacy measurement
definition: vaccine protection efficacy measurement is an assay that measures the protection efficayc of a vaccine.

LABEL: assay of CFU reduction in liver
definition: assay of CFU reduction in liver is a CFU reduction assay that is measured using the extracted liver as the tissue for isolation of infected pathogens.

LABEL: assay of CFU reduction in lung
definition: assay of CFU reduction in lung is a CFU reduction assay that is measured using the extracted lung as the tissue for isolation of infected pathogens.

LABEL: assay of CFU reduction in spleen
definition: assay of CFU reduction in spleen is a CFU reduction assay that is measured using the extracted spleen as the tissue for isolation of infected pathogens.

LABEL: hemagglutination-inhibition assay
definition: an immune response detection assay that detects specific antiviral antibodies in a test serum. The serum, usually a twofold dilution series, is mixed with a standard number, usually 4 to 8 HA units, of virus and incubated prior to the addition of a standard suspension of erythrocytes. The highest dilution of serum that inhibits hemagglutination is the HI titer of the serum. For example, influenza (AI) viruses agglutinate erythrocytes through the interaction of the virus surface glycoprotein, the hemagglutinin (HA), with receptors on the surface of the erythrocyte. Inhibition of the agglutination reaction by HA subtype-specific antisera is the basis of the hemagglutination-inhibition (HI) assay.

definition: artificial active immunization is an active immunization that occurs when a person or animal is vaccinated with a specific vaccine.

LABEL: induction of adaptive immune response to antigen
definition: induction of adaptive immune response to antigen is an active immunization process that results in induction of adaptive immune response to some antigens, for example, in a vaccine.

LABEL: modification of adaptive immune response to antigen
definition: modification of adaptive immune response to antigen is an active immunization process that results in modification of an adaptive immune response to some antigens, for example, in a therapeutic vaccine.

LABEL: natural active immunization
definition: natural active immunization is an active immunization that occur naturally when a person or animal comes in contact with antigens includeing microbes.

definition: a process of administering substance in vivo that involves in adding a vaccine into a host (e.g., human) in vivo with the intent to invoke a protective or therapeutic adaptive immune response.

LABEL: infection disorder prevention
definition: infection disorder prevention is a process that prevents a disorder that is the physical basis of an infectious disease.

LABEL: host response to vaccine adjuvant
definition: a process that specifies host response to a vaccine adjuvant.

LABEL: host response to vaccine antigen
definition: a process that specifies host response to a vaccine antigen.

LABEL: host response to vaccine vaccine vector
definition: a process that specifies host response to a vaccine vector.

LABEL: Th1-biased immune profile
definition: A biased immune profile that is characterized by the presense of T help cells Type 1 T helper (Th1) cells that produce interferon-gamma, interleukin (IL)-2, and tumour necrosis factor (TNF)-beta, which activate macrophages and are responsible for cell-mediated immunity and phagocyte-dependent protective responses.

LABEL: Th1/Th17 mixed immune profile
definition: An immune profile that is characterized by the presense of both Type 1 and Type 17 T helper  (Th1 and Th17) cells.

LABEL: Th1/Th2 mixed immune profile
definition: An immune profile that is characterized by the presense of both Type 1 and Type 2 T helper  (Th1 and Th2) cells.

LABEL: Th1/Th2/Th17 mixed immune profile
definition: An immune profile that is characterized by the presense of Type 1 Type 2, and Th17 T helper cells.

LABEL: Th17 immune profile
definition: An immune profile that is characterized by the presense of T helper 17 cells (Th17) that a subset of pro-inflammatory T helper cells defined by their production of interleukin 17 (IL-17). They are related to T regulatory cells and the signals that cause Th17s to differentiate actually inhibit Treg differentiation.

LABEL: Th2-biased immune profile
definition: A baised immune profile that is characterized by the presense of T type 2 Th (Th2) cells that produce IL-4, IL-5, IL-10, and IL-13, which are responsible for strong antibody production, eosinophil activation, and inhibition of several macrophage functions, thus providing phagocyte-independent protective responses.

LABEL: passive immunization
definition: Passive immunization is an immunization process where pre-synthesized elements of the immune system are transferred to an organism so that the body does not need to produce these elements itself.
editor note: Currently, antibodies can be used for passive immunization. This method of immunization works very quickly. However, it is short lasting. The antibodies are naturally broken down. If there are no B cells to produce more antibodies, they will disappear.|YH, XZ

LABEL: active immunization
definition: Active immunization is an immunization process that entails the introduction of a foreign molecule into the body, which causes the body itself to generate adaptive immunity against the target.

LABEL: passive immunization by injecting pre-made immune element
definition: passive immunization by injecting a recipient with pre-made antibody, antitoxin, epitope, etc.

LABEL: passive immunization using natural maternal antibody
definition: passive immunization that Immunity is transferred from mother to fetus through placental transfer of IgG or colostral transfer of IgA.

LABEL: intraperitoneal pathogen challenge
definition: intraperitoneal pathogen challenge is a pathogen challenge process that occurs in the intraperitoneal site of a host.

LABEL: survival assessment
definition: Survival assessment is an assay that measures the occurence of death events in one or more organisms that are monitored over time.
editor note: Need to point out more specifically that survival/death is measured.

LABEL: vaccine clinical trial
definition: A processual entity by which a vaccine is tested clinically for safety and effectiveness. Clinical trials are conducted in phases. Classically, clinical trials unfold in three phases in order to gather data and information about a vaccine and its performance. This will form the basis of a dossier submitted to regulatory authorities by way of an application for licensure. After a vaccine is licensed and is being used by large numbers of people, a Phase IV study may or may not be taken for vaccine clinical evaluation.
editor note:
Most vaccines against a pathogen (e.g., HIV) are not tested by vaccinating people and then deliberately exposing them to virulent pathogen (e.g., HIV). This strategy is never for a vaccine against a disease as serious as HIV.
The best way to determine if a vaccine is effective is to test it in a randomized, controlled, double-blind clinical trial. This type of trial is often referred to as the gold standard in medical research and provides the strongest evidence for the efficacy of a vaccine.

LABEL: vaccine approval process
definition: vaccine approval process is a processual entity that involves approval of a vaccine.

definition: A thymidine kinase-deficient mutant (PR1) is attenuated in mice and induced significant protection from challenge with wild type EHV-1 5 weeks after vaccination. In foals, PR1 also showed attenuation; however, the mutant induced only partial protection from challenge with EHV-1

LABEL: inactivation

LABEL: vaccine storage

LABEL: vaccine licensing

LABEL: phase 1 vaccine trial
definition: A vaccine clinical trial that investigates the safety profile of a vaccine in a small group (10-50) of healthy volunteers.

LABEL: phase 2 vaccine trial
definition: A vaccine clinical trial that studies vaccine efficacy with a target population (numbering 50-100). Different dosage levels will also be explored at this stage to determine the optimum dose.

LABEL: phase 3 vaccine trial
definition: A vaccine clinical trial that takes the trial to a large-scale safety and efficacy study in a relevant patient population, usually in excess of 3,000.

LABEL: phase 4 vaccine trial
definition: The final stage of vaccine clinical evaluation. Phase IV occurs after a vaccine or therapy is licensed and is being used by large numbers of people. These studies are not always required or completed.

LABEL: review of vaccine license application
definition: A vaccine regulatory process that is for vaccine regulatory agent to review vaccine license application from vaccine producer.

LABEL: vaccine license application
definition: A vaccine regulatory process that is for vaccine producer to apply for vaccine license.

LABEL: vaccine saftey regulation

LABEL: vaccine trial regulation
definition: A vaccine regulation process for vaccine clinical trials.

LABEL: vaccine storage at room temperature
definition: a vaccine storage that is execuated at room temperature. Room temperature is also referred to as ambient temperature. Room temperature denotes a certain temperature within enclosed space at which humans are accustomed. Room temperature is usually indicated by general human comfort, with the common range of 10 degree C (50 degree F) to 28 degree C (82.4 degree F).

definition: Secondary vaccination is a vaccination that is performed immediately after the primary or the first vaccination.

LABEL: quaternary vaccination

LABEL: intravesical vaccination

LABEL: percutaneous vaccination
definition: Administration of a drug by the way of absorption through the skin, usually for systemic action. The route allows sustained therapeutic plasma drug levels and avoids first pass effect. Simplicity of administration tends to result in high patient compliance.|YL
